Benha, a modern town in the Delta. The site of the ancient town, Hwt-hry-ib or Hwt-tA-hry-ib (Egyptian)/Athribis (Greek)/Atrib (Coptic), is located nearby at Tell Atrib. A hoard of coins, also known as the Delta Hoard, was found in 1929 and attributed to Benha el-Asl. The modern town of Benha has now expanded over and around the remains of the ancient site of Athribis so that only a small area of flat wasteland remains among the modern blocks of flats (the site of Polish excavations since 1986).

The term 'nome' refers to an administrative district of Ancient Egypt. The term nome (from the Greek “nomos” meaning district) came into usage from the Ptolemaic period (late 4th century BC onwards). This name replaced the original Egyptian district name “sepat”. The nome remained an administrative district until the early 4th century AD when smaller units, “pagi”, were formed. Over the years the borders of these nomes fluctuated but were mostly centred upon a town after which the nome was usually named, e.g. Memphis was the main town of the Memphite Nome. N.B. For places n Egypt, the term 'Gebel' is used in preference to 'Jebel' to reflect local pronounciation. For places in Sudan and the Middle East, the term 'Jebel' is used in preference.

Theban Tomb (TT) 320 is located next to Deir el-Bahari in the Theban necropolis and contained an extraordinary cache of mummified remains and funeral equipment of more than 50 kings, queens, royals and their nobility. The tomb may have originally belonged to the High Priest of Amun Pinedjem II, his wife Nesikhons and other close family members. At the time of Pinudjem’s death around 969 BC, mummies from former dynasties that were vulnerable to grave robbers were moved that in a collective efforts to protect them.

KV 35 in the Valley of the Kings in Egypt originally belonged to king Amenhotep II from the 18th Dynasty but was later used a mummy cache.
